Bioethics - Cases about resource-allocation
[
  {
  "id": 7,
  "premise": "You can give the only available kidney to a young patient or to an older patient, but not to both. Promoting others’ wellbeing is good.",
  "hypothesis": "You ought to give the kidney to the young patient.",
  "label": "Conflict within one principle",
  "explanation": "Given that you should promote others’ wellbeing, the younger patient’s need for a kidney is a reason to give the kidney to the younger patient. Given that you should promote others’ wellbeing, the older patient’s need is a reason to give the kidney to the older patient. Because the younger patient can benefit more from the transplant, the reason to give the kidney to the younger patient is stronger."
}

 {
  "id": 8,
  "premise": "You can give the only available kidney to a child or to an adult, but not to both. Promoting others’ wellbeing is good. In precedent 1, you could give the only available kidney to a young patient or an older patient. In precedent 1, you ought to give the kidney to the young patient.",
  "hypothesis": "You ought to give the kidney to the child.",
  "label": "Conflict within one principle (A fortiori reasoning)",
  "explanation": "Given that you should promote others’ wellbeing, the child’s need for a kidney is a reason to give the kidney to the child. Given that you should promote others’ wellbeing, the adult’s need is a reason to give the kidney to the adult. Since in the precedent case the reason to help the younger patient prevailed, and a child typically benefits even more than a young patient, the reason to give the kidney to the child is stronger here."
},

{
  "id": 9,
  "premise": "You can give the only available kidney to a patient who will die soon without it or to a patient whose condition is more stable, but not to both. Promoting others’ wellbeing is good.",
  "hypothesis": "You ought to give the kidney to the patient who will die soon.",
  "label": "Conflict within one principle",
  "explanation": "Given that you should promote others’ wellbeing, the urgent patient’s need for a kidney is a reason to give the kidney to the urgent patient. Given that you should promote others’ wellbeing, the stable patient’s need is a reason to give the kidney to the stable patient. Because the urgent patient is at immediate risk of death, the reason to help the urgent patient is stronger."
